\subsection{Two reader-side architectures: pull and intercept}
\label{sec:arch:pull-vs-intercept}

The architecture described above places the agent in the role of the
\emph{active reader}: the agent calls \texttt{trace.query} when it
estimates that peer events might inform its next decision.  This
design has the virtue of giving the agent control over what it asks
for, but pays four costs.

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item \emph{Decision overhead}: the agent must decide \emph{when} to
  query.  Empirically (\S\ref{sec:eval:results:travelplanner-isolation})
  the act of querying is more load-bearing than the ranker, so
  failures-to-query cost more than failures-to-rank.  Agents that
  forget to query miss the design's primary benefit.
\item \emph{Round-trip latency}: each \texttt{trace.query} is an LLM
  step (the agent emits the tool call) followed by a non-LLM step (the
  store returns events) followed by another LLM step (the agent reads
  the events and acts).
\item \emph{Adoption friction}: deploying ET-MCP in an existing agent
  framework requires modifying the agent's tool surface and prompting
  it to consider the new tool.
\item \emph{Near-circularity}: as observed in
  \S\ref{sec:eval:results:travelplanner-isolation}, the redundancy
  metric counts matches against in-store events, so the
  no\_query~$\to$~12.5\% contrast partially reflects
  ``agents who cannot read the store cannot avoid what is in the
  store.''
\end{enumerate}

The natural alternative is to relocate the reader from the agent to
the framework.  We define \textbf{intercept} as a passive reader-side
architecture: the orchestrator (or, in framework deployments, a
middleware layer) intercepts every tool call the agent emits and,
\emph{if} the call's \texttt{(name, arguments)} appears in the
task-scoped trace store as a peer event of type
\textsc{failed\_path} or \textsc{failed\_trial\_action}, prepends a
structured \texttt{[PEER-WARNING]} block to the tool's response before
returning it to the agent.

Concretely, intercept differs from pull on each of the four axes
above:

\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=*]
\item \emph{No decision overhead}: the agent does not decide when to
  consult peer events; the orchestrator consults them for every tool
  call as a side effect of tool execution.
\item \emph{No round-trip}: the warning rides on the response the
  agent is already going to receive.  There is no separate
  \texttt{trace.query} turn.
\item \emph{No agent code changes}: the agent's tool surface, system
  prompt, and prompt template are unchanged.  Intercept is deployable
  as a framework middleware on top of any LangChain-, AutoGen-, or
  MCP-based agent without recompiling agent logic.
\item \emph{No near-circularity}: the comparison
  intercept-vs-no\_coord asks ``does prepending a peer warning to a
  tool response change agent behavior?'' rather than ``does removing
  a query channel change matches against in-store events?''  The
  former is a clean causal test of the architecture; the latter is
  partially definitional.
\end{enumerate}

Intercept preserves the rest of ET-MCP's design vocabulary: the
event taxonomy (\S\ref{sec:arch:taxonomy}), the failure-only writer
policy, the task-scoped lifecycle, and the MCP-conformant transport
(the orchestrator queries the same MCP server the pull architecture
exposes, just from a different process and without an agent in the
loop).  It is, in short, the same coordination primitive
re-architected to remove the agent-as-reader assumption.

\paragraph{Deployability.}
The framework-level hook surface intercept rides on is already a
production primitive in deployed multi-agent runtimes.  Amazon's
Strands Agents SDK exposes \texttt{BeforeToolCallEvent} and
\texttt{AfterToolCallEvent}, the latter explicitly designed to
``rewrite the \texttt{ToolResultBlock} before it propagates to the
model''~\cite{strandshooks2025}.  Amazon Bedrock AgentCore Policy
``intercepts every tool call in real
time''~\cite{agentcorepolicy2025}.  LangChain middleware's
\texttt{wrap\_tool\_call} and \texttt{after\_model}
hooks~\cite{langchainmiddleware2026} and Microsoft Agent Framework's
function middleware~\cite{msagentframework2026} provide equivalent
mechanisms.  In all four cases the primitive is the same: a
framework layer that sits between agent and tool, can read both
sides of the call, and can rewrite the result before the agent's
next reasoning step.  These mechanisms are deployed today for
blocking, validation, retries, and caching; we contribute the
\emph{coordination semantics} that ride on top of the same hook
surface---a typed, task-scoped, negative-knowledge store keyed on
(tool name, arguments) tuples.  Intercept is therefore an additive
extension to existing production runtimes, not a new agent
framework.

